Title:
Tutorial example  - rotating frame for circular(*) polarization

# A similar problem as 13Circular400nm

# DESCRIPTION:
# Different from tutorial/13, choose the z-x plane
# as the polarization plane but operate in a rotating frame
# where z-axis remains aligned with the vector potential

# EXPLANATION
# if the laser frequency is low compared to any dynamics,
# i.e. when we are approaching adiabatic motion,
# the wavefunction expansion requires only low |m|-values
#
# NOTE: contrary to the preponderance of small L-M in circular polarization,
# the rotating frame can be used with arbitrary polarization, including non-planar

# ACCURACY
# relative accuracy of total spectrum <~ 1% with basis Eta=13, Phi=13
# (compare to tutorial/13Circular400nm)

# ALTERNATIVES
# rotating frame is an alterative to the (dynamical) adjustment of the basis.
# NOTE: Of course, also with a rotating frame dynamical basis can be used
# (as in the present example), but gains are small.

# TIMING:
# about 3.5 min total (laptop): 2 min calculation of surface, 1.5 min tSurff integration
# surfaces are stored wrt to the rotating frame
# when computing spectra, back-rotate to fixed frame is needed
# computation of amplitudes therefore is more expensive than fixed frame

#define Rc 20.

Spectrum: radialPoints=100, plot=total

Axis: name,nCoefficients,lower end, upper end,functions,order
 Phi,13,,,expIm
 Eta,13,-1,1, assocLegendre{Phi}
 Rn,32, 0.,Rc,polynomial,8
 Rn,20, Rc,Infty,polExp[1.]

Absorption: kind, axis, theta, upper
ECS,Rn,0.3,Rc

# Interaction for rotating frame:
#    a dc-Pulse with an angular correction that is proportional to the change of the angle
#    the correction operator "CoriolisTheta" is essentially the Ly angular momentum
#Operator: interaction='iLaserAabs[t]<<D/DZ>>+iLaserAdTheta[t]<<CoriolisTheta>>'
# below we use a shorthand for the above
Operator: interaction=<<LaserVelocityRotatingFrame>>

# here is what the field interaction would look like in fixed frame (needs all m's, Phi size 25)
# Operator: interaction='iLaserAx[t]<<D/DX>>+iLaserAz[t]<<D/DZ>>'

Operator: hamiltonian='1/2<<Laplacian>>-<1><1><trunc[15,20]/Q>'
Operator: expectationValue='<1><1><chi[0,20]>'

Laser: shape, I(W/cm2), FWHM, lambda(nm),phiCEO,polarAngle
cos2, 1e14, 2. OptCyc, 400.
cos2, 1e14, 2. OptCyc, 400.,pi/2,90.

TimePropagation: end,print,store,cutEnergy,accuracy,operatorThreshold
6 OptCyc, 0.05 OptCyc,0.5 au,50,1.e-7,0


